                        <li><strong>Lymphoma with CNS-IPI score 4-6</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>High-risk extranodal involvement:</strong> Testicular, breast, kidney, adrenal, uterine, ovarian</li>
                        <li><strong>High LDH levels</strong> in aggressive lymphoma</li>
                        <li><strong>Adult T-cell leukemia/lymphoma</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>Burkitt lymphoma</strong></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>CNS Prophylaxis Regimens</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <p><strong>Option 1: Intrathecal Chemotherapy</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Drug:</strong> Methotrexate 12 mg IT (or cytarabine 50-70 mg IT)</li>
                        <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> 4 doses during front-line therapy (typically with cycles 1-4)</li>
                        <li><strong>Route:</strong> Lumbar puncture or Ommaya reservoir</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <p><strong>Option 2: High-Dose Systemic Therapy</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Drugs:</strong> High-dose methotrexate (≥3 g/m²) OR high-dose cytarabine (≥2 g/m²)</li>
                        <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> 2 cycles after completion of front-line therapy</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Better CNS penetration than IT alone</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>CNS Lymphoma Treatment (Primary or Secondary)</h3>

                <div class="regimen-card">
                    <div class="regimen-header">
                        <span class="regimen-title">High-Dose MTX-based (MTR)</span>
                        <span class="badge cns">CNS</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="indication">
                        <strong>Indication:</strong> Primary CNS DLBCL or secondary CNS involvement
                    </div>

                    <table>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Drug</th>
                            <th>Dose</th>
                            <th>Schedule</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Methotrexate (M)</strong></td>
                            <td>3.5 g/m² IV over 4h</td>
                            <td>Day 1</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Leucovorin rescue</strong></td>
                            <td>15-25 mg IV/PO q6h</td>
                            <td>Starting Day 2 until MTX cleared (<0.1 μmol/L)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Rituximab (R)</strong></td>
                            <td>375 mg/m² IV</td>
                            <td>Day 3 (cycles 1-6 only)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Temozolomide (T)</strong></td>
                            <td>150 mg/m² PO daily</td>
                            <td>Days 7-11 of cycles 1, 3, 5, 7</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>

                    <p><strong>Cycle:</strong> 14 days × 7 cycles</p>

                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <h4>⚠️ MTX Drug Interactions - MUST HOLD</h4>
                        <p><strong>The following medications interfere with MTX clearance and MUST be held:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>PPIs</strong> (proton pump inhibitors) - use H2 blockers if needed</li>
                            <li><strong>Bactrim/TMP-SMX</strong> - switch to atovaquone for PJP prophylaxis</li>
                            <li><strong>Levofloxacin</strong> - use alternative antibiotic</li>
                            <li><strong>NSAIDs</strong> - avoid completely</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="resident-alert">
                        <h4>📋 MTX Clearance Schedule - CRITICAL</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Pre-MTX:</strong> Aggressive hydration (150-200 mL/hr NS), alkalinize urine (add bicarbonate to keep urine pH >7)</li>
                            <li><strong>MTX levels:</strong>
                                <ul style="margin-left:20px;">
                                    <li><strong>24h post-infusion:</strong> Goal <10 μmol/L</li>
                                    <li><strong>48h post-infusion:</strong> Goal <1 μmol/L</li>
                                    <li><strong>72h post-infusion:</strong> Goal <0.1 μmol/L</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><strong>If MTX not clearing:</strong>
                                <ul style="margin-left:20px;">
                                    <li>Increase leucovorin frequency to q3-4h and/or increase dose</li>
                                    <li>Increase IV fluids to 200-250 mL/hr</li>
                                    <li>Check urine pH (goal >7)</li>
                                    <li>Stat CMP (check creatinine)</li>
                                    <li>Page fellow AND pharmacy immediately</li>
                                </ul>
                            </li>
                            <li><strong>Monitor:</strong> Daily BMP, Mg, Phos during MTX clearance</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <h4>⚠️ Overnight MTX Management</h4>
                        <p><strong>If concerned about MTX toxicity or delayed clearance overnight:</strong></p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Order STAT CMP and MTX level</li>
                            <li>Increase leucovorin to q3-4h if level elevated</li>
                            <li>Page fellow immediately</li>
                            <li>Page pharmacy for dosing recommendations</li>
                            <li>Ensure IV fluids running at appropriate rate</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- ADVANCED THERAPIES -->
            <section id="advanced" class="section">
                <h2>CAR-T & Bispecific Antibodies</h2>

                <h3>CAR-T Cell Therapy</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <p><strong>FDA-approved CAR-T for lymphoma:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Axicabtagene ciloleucel (Yescarta)</strong> - CD19-targeted</li>
                        <li><strong>Tisagenlecleucel (Kymriah)</strong> - CD19-targeted</li>
                        <li><strong>Lisocabtagene maraleucel (Breyanzi)</strong> - CD19-targeted</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Indications:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Relapsed/refractory large B-cell lymphoma after ≥2 prior lines</li>
                        <li>Relapsed/refractory follicular lymphoma after ≥2 prior lines</li>
                        <li>Primary refractory or early relapse (<12 months) DLBCL</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="resident-alert">
                    <h4>📋 CAR-T Process Overview</h4>
                    <ol>
                        <li><strong>Leukapheresis:</strong> Collect patient T-cells</li>
                        <li><strong>Manufacturing:</strong> 2-4 weeks (patient may need bridging chemo)</li>
                        <li><strong>Lymphodepletion:</strong> Fludarabine + cyclophosphamide × 3 days</li>
                        <li><strong>CAR-T infusion:</strong> Single infusion (outpatient possible in some centers)</li>
                        <li><strong>Monitoring:</strong> Close follow-up for CRS/ICANS (Days 1-14 highest risk)</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>

                <h3>Epcoritamab (Bispecific T-Cell Engager)</h3>

                <div class="regimen-card">
                    <div class="regimen-header">
                        <span class="regimen-title">Epcoritamab (Epkinly)</span>
                        <span class="badge relapsed">Relapsed/Refractory</span>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="indication">
                        <strong>Indication:</strong> Relapsed/refractory DLBCL after ≥3 prior lines of therapy
                    </div>

                    <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> CD20 (B-cell) × CD3 (T-cell) bispecific antibody</p>

                    <table>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Phase</th>
                            <th>Dose</th>
                            <th>Schedule</th>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Priming Doses (Cycle 1)</strong></td>
                            <td>0.16 mg → 0.8 mg SQ</td>
                            <td>Days 1 and 8</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Full Dose</strong></td>
                            <td>48 mg SQ</td>
                            <td>Day 15, then weekly × 9 doses, then q2 weeks × 9 doses, then q4 weeks</td>
                        </tr>
                    </table>

                    <div class="warning-box">
                        <h4>⚠️ CRS Risk with Bispecific Antibodies</h4>
                        <p><strong>Highest risk:</strong> After first full dose (Day 15 of Cycle 1)</p>
                        <p><strong>Management:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Hospitalize for first full dose (48h observation)</li>
                            <li>Pre-medications: Dexamethasone, acetaminophen, diphenhydramine</li>
                            <li>Have tocilizumab readily available</li>
                            <li>Monitor vitals q4h × 24h after dose</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- GLOSSARY -->
            <section id="glossary" class="glossary">
                <h3>📚 Abbreviations & Glossary</h3>
                
                <div class="abbrev">
                    <span class="abbrev-term">DLBCL</span>
